.TH _PRINTF 3 "2026-01-11" "1.0" "Custom _printf Function"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output to stdout

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "#include <stdarg.h>"
.sp
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function produces output on the standard output (stdout) according to the format string
.B format
and additional arguments. It behaves similarly to the standard C
.B printf
function but supports only a limited set of conversion specifiers.

Currently supported conversion specifiers:
.IP "\fB%d\fR, \fB%i\fR"
Prints a signed decimal integer.
.IP "\fB%c\fR"
Prints a single character.
.IP "\fB%s\fR"
Prints a null-terminated string. If the string is NULL, "(null)" is printed.
.IP "\fB%%\fR"
Prints a literal percent sign '%'.

Unsupported features:
.RS
- Flags (e.g., '+', '0', '#', ' ')
- Field width
- Precision
- Length modifiers (e.g., 'l', 'h')
- Conversion specifiers other than %d, %i, %c, %s, %%
.RE

If a trailing '%' appears in the format string without a following valid specifier, _printf returns -1 and prints nothing.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, _printf returns the total number of characters printed.  
If an error occurs (e.g., format string is NULL, or a trailing '%' is present), it returns -1.

.SH EXAMPLES
Print an integer and a string:
.RS
.nf
_printf("Number: %d, String: %s\n", 42, "Hello");
.fi
.RE

Print a literal percent sign:
.RS
.nf
_printf("Progress: 100%% complete\n");
.fi
.RE

Print a character:
.RS
.nf
_printf("First letter: %c\n", 'A');
.fi
.RE

.SH AUTHOR
Implemented by Tural Gasimov, 2026.

.SH NOTES
This implementation is designed for educational purposes, following the simplified requirements of the Holberton `_printf` project. It uses a dynamic buffer internally to safely handle long strings.

